The Kodiak Island Borough School District will continue to serve free meals to kids ages 1-18.

Starting September 8 through December 31, 2020, students enrolled in traditional school will be provided meals at their school site.

Students enrolled in Homeschool, the Kodiak Remote Learning School, and any other children ages 1-18 may pick up their meals at Kodiak High School, under the digital sign, from 9am to 11am.

Meal service runs Monday through Friday.

Parents/Guardians:
As we prepare for the 2020-2021 school year, family input is important. Please take a moment to answer a few questions that will allow us to better prepare for your needs in the fall. The survey should take less than 5 minutes. Thank you in advance!

Mahal naming mga Magulang o Tagapag-alaga:
Habang tayo ay naghahanda para sa pasukan sa taong 2020-2021 ang tugon ng pamilya ay mahalaga. Maglaan ng kaunting oras para sagutin ang ilang mga katanungan para makatulong at makapaghanda kami ng mabuti para sa pangangailangan ninyo sa Taglagas.

Estimados Padres/Tutores:
A medida que nos preparamos para el año escolar 2020-2021, el aporte familiar es importante. Por favor, tómese un momento para responder algunas preguntas que nos permitirán prepararnos mejor para sus necesidades en el otoño.

post_text:
Have you ever thought of becoming a substitute teacher? If so, now is the perfect time to apply!

Substitutes play a valuable role in the daily functions of our schools. In preparation for the upcoming school year, KIBSD is seeking substitutes for a wide range of positions throughout the district: classroom teachers, day custodians, cooks/cook helpers, school nurses (requires current Alaska R.N. license) and classroom aides.

For full job descriptions, requirements, and to apply online, visit: https://www.applitrack.com/alaskateacher/onlineapp/default.aspx?Category=Substitute

If you have questions, please call the District Office at 907-486-7550.

post_text:
Youth Ambassador Program (ages 16 & 17)

Interested in earning money while serving your state? Be a Youth Vote Ambassador worker.

Your community needs YOU! The Youth Vote Ambassador Program is designed to enliven your interest in the political process and help you learn your rights and responsibilities as a citizen.

Work at polling places on Election Day by checking-in voters, confirming registration status and activating voting machines.

Gain real-life experience that you may be able to apply towards a school project.

Your local election officials can teach you everything you need to know to do the job.

Visit the Alaska Division of Elections website for full details.

Applications can be sent to Jamie Bulter at jamie.butler@kibsd.org

post_text:
KHS Shakesbears are AK Spirit of Youth grant winners!

On Tuesday, the KHS Shakesbears won a $1500 grant from the Alaska Spirit of Youth and the Alaska Department of Health and Social Services as part of their competitive COVID-19 Youth Messaging Grant.

A group of teen Spirit of Youth judges awarded the Shakesbears for their proposed project to produce a podcast that encourages positive activities and mental health to reach their peers during the COVID-19 pandemic. The Shakesbears are partnering with KMXT to produce a four-episode interview podcast series called "Jared Talks to Teens" that will feature improv comedy and some wacky characters.

The podcast will be produced over the next few weeks, air on KMXT, and then archived in other podcast mediums and made available to other statewide radio outlets. The grant will be used to compensate teen podcast producers and writers, and for recording equipment and KMXT staff assistance.

We're really excited about this new opportunity that will broaden the Shakesbears' theatrical reach across the state!
text:
KHS Shakesbears are AK Spirit of Youth grant winners!

On Tuesday, the KHS Shakesbears won a $1500 grant from the Alaska Spirit of Youth and the Alaska Department of Health and Social Services as part of their competitive COVID-19 Youth Messaging Grant.

A group of teen Spirit of Youth judges awarded the Shakesbears for their proposed project to produce a podcast that encourages positive activities and mental health to reach their peers during the COVID-19 pandemic. The Shakesbears are partnering with KMXT to produce a four-episode interview podcast series called "Jared Talks to Teens" that will feature improv comedy and some wacky characters.

The podcast will be produced over the next few weeks, air on KMXT, and then archived in other podcast mediums and made available to other statewide radio outlets. The grant will be used to compensate teen podcast producers and writers, and for recording equipment and KMXT staff assistance.

We're really excited about this new opportunity that will broaden the Shakesbears' theatrical reach across the state!

shared_text:
Kodiak Arts Council added 21 new photos to the album: Kodiak Mayors' Youth Poster Design Contest — in Kodiak, Alaska.
April 17 at 11:10 AM · Kodiak, AK ·

Recognizing that the arts have the power to spark joy, inspire action, and promote togetherness, the mayors of the City of Kodiak and Kodiak Island Borough co-sponsored a "Kodiak Strong" Poster Design Contest for local youth.

We received a total of 74 entries highlighting Kodiak's response to COVID-19 with themes including social distancing, staying home, playing outside safely, caring for elders, caring for others, healthcare worker appreciation, and more. Students expressed themselves with watercolors, paints, crayons, markers, collage, and graphic design programs.

Enjoy this gallery of the selected winners in each age group. Galleries of all entries can be found on the Kodiak Arts Council website (www.kodiakarts.org)

Special thanks to our judges, and to partnering organizations City of Kodiak, Kodiak Island Borough, Kodiak Island Borough School District, Kodiak History Museum, Kodiak Chamber of Commerce, Kodiak Rotary Clubs, Kodiak Lions Club.

Graduating Class of 2020 Family Survey

Parents/Guardians,

Please take a moment to complete the graduation survey for our class of 2020. By sharing your ideas and input, you will help us to develop a plan as we work to make a memorable graduation ceremony during these unprecedented times. Let’s create a historic graduation that will be remembered, for good reasons, for the next one-hundred years. The survey can be accessed at the following link: https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/9HY7JCZ.

Additionally, we will be holding two virtual planning meetings via BlueJeans. These will take place on Friday, April 24 and Friday, May 1 at 6:30 pm. Here is the link to participate https://primetime.bluejeans.com/a2m/live-event/thaphfss. Once you join the BlueJeans meeting you will be able to hear the speaker, and will have the option of “raising your hand” to request to interact with the group.

We Are Kodiak!

Mel LeVan, Principal
Neil Hecht, Assistant Principal
Joyce Blair, Assistant Principal

post_text:
Congratulations to Phyllis Amodo on receiving the Region II ASAA Female Coach of the Year Award!

"There is no greater feeling quite like helping young athletes. Watching their talent and dedication grow into a skill that we all can be proud of. Just to be able to see their smile when they have reached their goal. As a coach, one of the greatest successes I’ll know is helping others succeed and grow. What an honor it has been to coach past and present KESS student-athletes.

I can not express how grateful I am for the opportunity that I have had to coach the KESS team over the past four years. I have had the pleasure of coaching a wonderful group of student-athletes. My team has always exhibited fantastic sportsmanship on and off the court. I am honored to receive this award."

Coach Amodo

What do you do when your students reach their reading goal? Naturally, you kiss a goat!

East Elementary School Principal, Mrs. Hietala promised students she would honor their request to kiss a real goat if they met their school-wide reading step goal of 70,000. Not only did they reach their goal they surpassed it by an additional 13,906 steps! Staying true to her word Mrs. Hietala kissed a real goat during an assembly held last Friday. Way to go East readers, and thank you Mrs. Hietala for being such a good sport!

Mr. Daly arrived with a cooler containing several live King Crab. Students learned many things about King Crabs including the molting process and where they store their eggs. Not surprisingly, they were most excited to feel their shells and touch their spiny legs.

post_text:
Monday night’s School Board meeting was full of well deserved recognitions. The Board presented certificates to Kodiak High School students Leigh Bruno and Graciano Suralta who achieved their Certified Nursing Assistant certification through the KHS CNA program. Elizabeth Erickson also completed the CNA program but was unable to attend the meeting. The Board also recognized their teacher, Sonia Egdorf, for her “valuable contribution in the development and implementation of the Certified Nursing Assistant Program” for KHS/KIBSD.

Lastly, the Board recognized Steve Johnston and Whitney McElwain as Volunteers of the Month from Kodiak High and Port Lions Schools. Thank you for all you do for our students!
